description:
When animation reaches the last step, PlaybackController.playing becomes false. If the user clicks Play again, play() at line 32-35 checks `this.currentIndex >= this.steps.length` and silently returns. The user must click Stop first, then Play.

Fix: In play(), if currentIndex is at the last step (or beyond), reset to 0 before starting:
```ts
play(): void {
  if (this.playing) return;
  if (this.currentIndex >= this.steps.length - 1) {
    this.currentIndex = 0;
    this.onStep(this.steps[0], 0);
  }
  this.playing = true;
  this.scheduleNext();
}
```

GraphVisualizer.tsx:131-134 builds a `new Map()` of node positions on every render:
```ts
const nodePos = new Map<string, { x: number; y: number }>();
for (const n of graph.nodes) { nodePos.set(n.id, { x: n.x, y: n.y }); }
```

This runs on every step change (every ~100-500ms during playback). The graph structure doesn't change between steps.

Fix: Wrap in useMemo with [graph.nodes] dependency:
```ts
const nodePos = useMemo(() => {
  const map = new Map<string, { x: number; y: number }>();
  for (const n of graph.nodes) { map.set(n.id, { x: n.x, y: n.y }); }
  return map;
}, [graph.nodes]);
```

GeometryVisualizer.tsx:111-112 calls `getHullEdges(mutations)` and `getStack(mutations)` on every render. These functions parse JSON from VisualMutation label strings. While the results ARE used in subsequent useMemo calls, the parsing itself is redundant when mutations haven't changed.

Fix: Wrap in useMemo:
```ts
const { hullVertexIds, stackIds } = useMemo(() => ({
  hullVertexIds: getHullEdges(mutations),
  stackIds: getStack(mutations),
}), [mutations]);
```

Note: `mutations` is derived from `step?.mutations ?? []`, which changes on every step. But the useMemo still helps because the downstream `hullEdges` and `stackEdges` useMemos depend on these values — having stable references avoids cascading recomputation.

When switching between algorithm categories (e.g., Sorting → Graph), the input section instantly swaps. The vizType-conditional rendering in AlgorithmPanel (lines 801-1217) has no transition — the old inputs vanish and new ones appear.

Add AnimatePresence from motion/react to wrap the conditional input sections:
```tsx
<AnimatePresence mode="wait">
  <motion.div
    key={vizType}
    initial={{ opacity: 0, y: 8 }}
    animate={{ opacity: 1, y: 0 }}
    exit={{ opacity: 0, y: -8 }}
    transition={{ duration: 0.15 }}
  >
    {/* input section */}
  </motion.div>
</AnimatePresence>
```

Also add subtle slide-in for the playback controls section when it first appears (after clicking Run).
